Yes. Since this is an FDP, faculty members should leave with something they have built, not just listened to. Here are practical 1-hour hands-on activities for each session.


Git & GitHub Fundamentals Challenge
Title
"My First Academic Repository"
Objective
Each faculty member will create and manage their own GitHub repository for a course or research project.
Tasks
Task 1 (10 min): Create a GitHub Repository
Repository name: AI-in-Education or <Department>-Course-Materials
Add a README file.
Task 2 (10 min): Clone the Repository
Clone it to the local computer.
Open it in VS Code.
Task 3 (15 min): Create Academic Content
 Create:
LessonPlan.md
Syllabus.md
Resources.md
Add basic content.
Task 4 (10 min): Git Commands
 Run:
git status
git add .
git commit -m "Added lesson plan"
git push
Task 5 (10 min): Edit and Update
 Modify LessonPlan.md and push a second commit.
Task 6 (5 min): Reflection
 View the commit history and explain how version control helps maintain academic materials.
Learning Outcome
Faculty understand repositories, commits, version history, and collaborative content management.

